      "text": "[[Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP]] (DASH), also known as [[MPEG-DASH]], is an adaptive bitrate streaming technique that enables high quality streaming of media content over the Internet delivered from conventional HTTP web servers - [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_Adaptive_Streaming_over_HTTP wikipedia]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "599dd9a0-5515-4b93-af7f-84053d70ef99",
      "text": "Unlike HLS, HDS, and Smooth Streaming, DASH is codec-agnostic, which means it can use content encoded with any coding format like H.265, H.264, VP9 etc."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "03431fd70ff8b28a",
      "text": "Similar to Apple's HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) solution, MPEG-DASH works by breaking the content into a sequence of small HTTP-based file segments, each segment containing a short interval of playback time of content that is potentially many hours in duration, such as a movie or the live broadcast of a sports event. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f842930f4d1f4bcf",
      "text": "The content is made available at a variety of different bit rates, i.e., alternative segments encoded at different bit rates covering aligned short intervals of playback time. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2d4a97b9ab9bc89e",
      "text": "While the content is being played back by an MPEG-DASH client, the client automatically selects from the alternatives the next segment to download and play based on current network conditions. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "253ba969d2c95de3",
      "text": "The client selects the segment with the highest bit rate possible that can be downloaded in time for playback without causing stalls or re-buffering events in the playback. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7a5dc2bf92eb930",
